### Method Overriding in C#

Method overriding allows a derived class to provide a specific implementation of a method defined in its base class.

### Requirements

1. Base class method must be marked with `virtual`, `abstract`, or `override`
2. Derived class method must use the `override` keyword
3. Method signature (name, return type, parameters) must match exactly

### Virtual and Override

```csharp
public class Base
{
    public virtual void Show()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Base implementation");
    }
}

public class Derived : Base
{
    public override void Show()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Derived implementation");
    }
}
```

### Calling Base Implementation

```csharp
public class Derived : Base
{
    public override void Show()
    {
        base.Show();  // Call base version
        Console.WriteLine("Then add derived behavior");
    }
}
```

### Override vs New

| Aspect | override | new |
|--------|----------|-----|
| Polymorphism | Yes (runtime) | No (compile-time) |
| Base method | Must be virtual/abstract/override | Can be any method |
| Intent | Extend/replace behavior | Hide base method |

```csharp
Base b = new Derived();
b.Show();  // override -> "Derived"; new -> "Base"
```

### Sealed Override

Stop further overriding:

```csharp
public class Base
{
    public virtual void Show() { }
}

public class Derived : Base
{
    public sealed override void Show() { }
}

public class MoreDerived : Derived
{
    // public override void Show() { }  // Error - sealed
}
```

### Overriding Properties

```csharp
public class Base
{
    public virtual string Name { get; set; }
}

public class Derived : Base
{
    private string _name;

    public override string Name
    {
        get => _name.ToUpper();
        set => _name = value;
    }
}
```

### Rules for Overriding

| Rule | Explanation |
|------|-------------|
| Same signature | Name, parameters, return type must match |
| Cannot override static | Static methods are not virtual |
| Cannot override non-virtual | Base method must be virtual, abstract, or override |
| Access level | Override must have same or greater access |
| Covariant return types | C# 9+ allows more specific return type |

### Covariant Return Types (C# 9+)

```csharp
public class Base
{
    public virtual Base Clone() => new Base();
}

public class Derived : Base
{
    public override Derived Clone() => new Derived();
}
```

> **Key Point:** Use `override` to replace behavior polymorphically. Use `new` to hide a method (not polymorphic). Always call `base.MethodName()` if you want to extend the base behavior. Use `sealed override` to prevent further overrides in the inheritance chain.

### Abstract Override

```csharp
public abstract class Base
{
    public abstract void MustImplement();
}

public class Derived : Base
{
    public override void MustImplement() { }
}
```

codeExample:
using System;

public class Account
{
    public virtual decimal CalculateInterest(decimal balance)
    {
        return balance * 0.01m;  // 1% base rate
    }
}

public class SavingsAccount : Account
{
    public override decimal CalculateInterest(decimal balance)
    {
        return balance * 0.03m;  // 3% for savings
    }
}

public class PremiumAccount : Account
{
    public override decimal CalculateInterest(decimal balance)
    {
        return base.CalculateInterest(balance) + balance * 0.02m;
    }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Account[] accounts = { new Account(), new SavingsAccount(), new PremiumAccount() };
        foreach (var acc in accounts)
            Console.WriteLine($"Interest: {acc.CalculateInterest(1000):C}");
    }
}
